Search Fields
A Search Field is a type of text field in which a user enters text that is used to perform a search. The images
below show the different possible states of a search field and try to envision a generic search widget that
can be utilized in a variety of applications and in a variety of contexts.
Insensitive - In this state, the user cannot
interact with the entry. It is helpful to hint at
this widget's purpose with the search icon,
but it is not helpful to include any text that
implies interaction.
Unfocused - This is the 'resting' state of the
widget: how it should appear before a user
attempts to manipulate it. We again hint with
the icon, but also include text as to explicitly
instruct a user how to interact with this field.

Search in Progress - In the case where a search
is not instant, progress must be indicated. You
can also see that the icon on the right has
changed from a "clear" button to "stop" in
order to allow a user to halt the search.
Search Options - An application may wish to
provide multiple search methods (A web
browser with Google, Yahoo! etc). In this case
the search icon should be accompanied by a
small arrow and produce a menu when clicked.

Focused - In this state, the user has selected
the entry. The text is cleared in orer to indicate
that the entry is ready to accept the user's
input.
Typing - When a user begins typing, the "clear"
button should appear on the right on the entry.
Searching should provide live results and also
provide autocompletion when possible.
